1
00:02:29,220 --> 00:02:31,220
If you say "No"...

2
00:02:31,324 --> 00:02:34,324
...oil wells will be ours...

3
00:02:34,858 --> 00:02:38,258
...and we will decide
what to do with them!

4
00:02:48,317 --> 00:02:50,317
Thank you.

5
00:02:50,546 --> 00:02:52,546
If you say "No"...

6
00:02:54,777 --> 00:02:59,704
...we won't sell out
to foreign interests...

7
00:02:59,705 --> 00:03:02,111
...not even if they rub
their money in our faces,

8
00:03:02,112 --> 00:03:05,412
as if they're having a feast
before starving people.

9
00:03:58,249 --> 00:03:59,849
<i>Ambulance!</i>

10
00:04:00,600 --> 00:04:02,788
<i>Stay with him, stay with him!
Get the mic down.</i>

11
00:04:02,789 --> 00:04:04,089
Got a two-shot?

12
00:04:04,477 --> 00:04:07,577
- Ambulance!
Keep down the mic, keep it down.

13
00:04:08,126 --> 00:04:09,626
Keep shooting!

14
00:04:09,706 --> 00:04:11,606
Somebody bring an ambulance!

15
00:04:11,669 --> 00:04:13,669
Stay close. Watch out!

16
00:04:13,790 --> 00:04:15,489
An ambulance, for Christ's sake!

17
00:04:15,875 --> 00:04:17,575
Get this shot, right here!

18
00:04:18,132 --> 00:04:20,932
Go away! Go away!
<i>Keep shooting. Bring it around.</i>

19
00:04:21,032 --> 00:04:22,687
Go away!

20
00:04:23,255 --> 00:04:26,022
Roberto, let's go.
It's dangerous out here, come on.

21
00:04:26,023 --> 00:04:28,123
Not until an ambulance arrives.

22
00:04:28,223 --> 00:04:29,924
The ambulance and a doctor
are already on the way.

23
00:04:29,925 --> 00:04:31,519
- Are you sure?
- Yes, positive. Let's go.

24
00:04:31,520 --> 00:04:33,520
- Are you sure?
- Let's go, let's go.

25
00:04:47,150 --> 00:04:49,232
<i>Roberto! Roberto!</i>

26
00:04:49,782 --> 00:04:51,250
Come on, hurry!

27
00:04:53,451 --> 00:04:55,451
Cut, cut, cut!

28
00:05:28,152 --> 00:05:30,352
So, who did it? The guerillas?

29
00:05:31,301 --> 00:05:32,701
Maybe.

30
00:05:33,711 --> 00:05:35,711
Christ, you were terrific!

31
00:05:35,883 --> 00:05:37,783
It was an incredible moment!

32
00:05:38,850 --> 00:05:40,371
I'm gonna cut the film
tonight in New York...

33
00:05:40,372 --> 00:05:42,572
...and have it flown back
down tomorrow.

34
00:05:43,216 --> 00:05:46,716
We're gonna take this thing.
We're gonna take it.

35
00:05:47,134 --> 00:05:49,134
When are you coming back?

36
00:05:50,029 --> 00:05:53,729
I don't know yet, but I've gone over
everything with Miguel.

37
00:05:54,026 --> 00:05:55,735
He's gonna be handling...

38
00:05:55,736 --> 00:05:58,036
...all the print contracts,
the billboards, the posters.

39
00:05:58,171 --> 00:06:01,187
He also's gonna be having
the payroll,

40
00:06:01,188 --> 00:06:04,888
which includes the reporters.
I gave him a list already.

41
00:06:07,508 --> 00:06:10,408
From now until the election,

42
00:06:11,702 --> 00:06:14,102
every speech, every appearance,

43
00:06:14,440 --> 00:06:16,640
you're gonna wear this shirt.

44
00:06:17,888 --> 00:06:21,088
You keep your jacket on
till just before the finish,

45
00:06:21,749 --> 00:06:23,749
then slowly take it off...

46
00:06:23,908 --> 00:06:27,647
...and you just stand there,
let the whole country see it.

47
00:06:27,747 --> 00:06:31,047
<i>"They want to hurt us,
they want to destroy us,"</i>

48
00:06:31,203 --> 00:06:33,605
<i>"but they'll spill our blood
before they defeat us."</i>

49
00:06:33,606 --> 00:06:35,206
Blah, blah, blah, blah.

50
00:07:24,746 --> 00:07:26,349
<i>Nice trip, Mr. St. John?</i>

51
00:07:26,449 --> 00:07:28,505
- Tired?
- I can't tell yet.

52
00:07:28,506 --> 00:07:30,152
We booked the mixing room
for the rest of the night.

53
00:07:30,153 --> 00:07:32,541
- Did you bring the film?
- Yeah, but I wanna clean up a bit.

54
00:07:32,542 --> 00:07:35,299
I want you to stick around
when I do the cuts.

55
00:07:36,398 --> 00:07:39,006
I assume you found some decent
talent for the voice-over.

56
00:07:39,007 --> 00:07:40,495
No, I found some great talent.

57
00:07:40,496 --> 00:07:42,500
He's an actor.
He does Spanish soaps here.

58
00:07:42,501 --> 00:07:44,908
He used to be a radio announcer
in South America.

59
00:07:44,909 --> 00:07:47,099
Mom, I hope you didn't wait up.

60
00:07:47,825 --> 00:07:50,756
God, you look like shit.
And this is only March.

61
00:07:50,757 --> 00:07:52,793
What will you look like
in November?

62
00:07:52,794 --> 00:07:54,094
I don't know.

63
00:07:54,167 --> 00:07:56,333
I had him talk to my friend
Patricia, and according to her,

64
00:07:56,334 --> 00:07:58,334
he has a very sexy accent.

65
00:07:58,777 --> 00:08:01,068
I advise you to wrap this thing up
early tonight because...

66
00:08:01,069 --> 00:08:03,049
...Wallace Furman is coming
in the morning.

67
00:08:03,050 --> 00:08:06,450
- For how long?
- Definitely, no longer than all day.

68
00:08:07,217 --> 00:08:08,517
What did Ellen want?

69
00:08:08,581 --> 00:08:11,620
She said some decent information,
for a change.

70
00:08:11,720 --> 00:08:13,105
You're having dinner
tomorrow night with...

71
00:08:13,106 --> 00:08:16,097
-...Senator Hastings and his wife.
- In Washington?

72
00:08:16,169 --> 00:08:18,653
Yeah, the plane will be
at LaGuardia at 6:00.

73
00:08:18,654 --> 00:08:20,927
Even with traffic, you should
get there by 8:30.

74
00:08:20,928 --> 00:08:22,773
You pulled the file
from the last campaign?

75
00:08:22,774 --> 00:08:25,040
Yeah.
Also the Stannard files.

76
00:08:25,540 --> 00:08:26,961
Oh, Garber called last week.

77
00:08:26,962 --> 00:08:29,159
We pushed your meeting
up to the 12th.

78
00:08:29,160 --> 00:08:32,060
You'll go to Seattle
right out of D.C.

79
00:08:32,173 --> 00:08:35,073
I'll go there tomorrow and
brief them on the new numbers.

80
00:08:35,778 --> 00:08:37,278
You did good.

81
00:08:37,444 --> 00:08:39,044
Syd, you are sensational!

82
00:08:39,867 --> 00:08:41,442
No problem!

83
00:08:41,692 --> 00:08:43,767
You're my kind of guy.

84
00:08:44,144 --> 00:08:45,444
And what kind is that?

85
00:08:45,540 --> 00:08:47,040
Temporary.

86
00:08:49,829 --> 00:08:52,011
So, let us move ahead,

87
00:08:52,012 --> 00:08:56,129
with energy,
with compassion, and...

88
00:08:56,811 --> 00:09:00,911
...united by the vision
of what New Mexico can be...

89
00:09:01,005 --> 00:09:04,005
<i>...if only we dare
to make it so.</i>

90
00:09:04,966 --> 00:09:05,984
Darling,

91
00:09:06,034 --> 00:09:08,166
you are so positive.

92
00:09:08,360 --> 00:09:10,649
- No, I'm not.
- Your strength flows right off--

93
00:09:10,650 --> 00:09:13,000
- Oh, no, please--
- I'm not just saying that!

94
00:09:13,001 --> 00:09:14,901
- I was terrible.
- You're so strong...

95
00:09:14,902 --> 00:09:17,509
...in a nice, understated way.
Now, granted,

96
00:09:17,559 --> 00:09:21,000
I may be a bit biased, Mr. St. John,
but you have got to admit that...

97
00:09:21,001 --> 00:09:24,195
...Wallace has just got
that certain-- you know.

98
00:09:24,284 --> 00:09:27,084
Mrs. Furman, Wallace,
I'll be right down.

99
00:09:28,880 --> 00:09:31,336
Are you sure you want to handle
this campaign?

100
00:09:31,436 --> 00:09:33,836
- Why?
- Why?

101
00:09:33,956 --> 00:09:38,056
If this guy were masturbating
his hand would fall asleep.

102
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:40,500
We have nothing to lose.

103
00:09:40,571 --> 00:09:43,557
Anything that gets over 39%
makes us look good.

104
00:09:43,657 --> 00:09:45,957
And it pays the overhead.

105
00:09:50,554 --> 00:09:52,706
Wallace, you're running
for governor.

106
00:09:52,707 --> 00:09:54,748
It's not gonna be easy.

107
00:09:54,848 --> 00:09:58,015
What we're aiming for here,
the ideal,

108
00:09:58,016 --> 00:10:01,281
is that you personify
the themes of the campaign.

109
00:10:01,382 --> 00:10:04,482
That you make a statement
just by standing up. Now,

110
00:10:04,539 --> 00:10:06,739
our themes are:

111
00:10:06,875 --> 00:10:09,275
new ideas, new directions.

112
00:10:09,752 --> 00:10:12,052
Change! Vigor!

113
00:10:12,706 --> 00:10:15,201
No offense, but you look
too soft to change a tire...

114
00:10:15,202 --> 00:10:17,502
- ...much less a state.
- That's ridiculous.

115
00:10:17,596 --> 00:10:20,196
- What are you saying?
- He's saying you're a wimp.

116
00:10:20,322 --> 00:10:21,712
What I'm saying is,

117
00:10:21,713 --> 00:10:24,522
you've got to align
the perception with the reality.

118
00:10:24,626 --> 00:10:27,033
<i>We've got two immediate problems.
One, you were born into money.</i>

119
00:10:27,034 --> 00:10:29,164
<i>Two, you did it out of state,
which wasn't too smart,</i>

120
00:10:29,165 --> 00:10:32,365
<i>but these are turnable,
we'll manage this whole thing.</i>

121
00:10:33,451 --> 00:10:35,990
All right, I want you to go
on a high protein diet...

122
00:10:35,991 --> 00:10:37,504
...and start working out
on a Nautilus,

123
00:10:37,505 --> 00:10:39,401
three times a week,
minimum.

124
00:10:39,466 --> 00:10:42,158
We also gotta work on punching up
this delivery of yours.

125
00:10:42,159 --> 00:10:45,150
And energize it, make it track
with the message. Okay?

126
00:10:45,151 --> 00:10:47,351
- Yeah, okay.
- Now let's talk about colors.

127
00:10:47,444 --> 00:10:49,282
Syd's gonna take you
to this guy on 57th Street...

128
00:10:49,283 --> 00:10:52,683
...for a couple of dozen shirts,
once we get set on the shades.

129
00:10:52,842 --> 00:10:55,142
I don't like you in blue or gray.
Too cold for you.

130
00:10:55,608 --> 00:10:57,608
You're running
in New Mexico.

131
00:10:57,762 --> 00:10:59,502
You look a little
washed out.

132
00:10:59,552 --> 00:11:01,362
Don't you ever
get outside at all?

133
00:11:01,431 --> 00:11:03,403
I've asked him
to stay out of the sun...

134
00:11:03,404 --> 00:11:06,704
...because his family has
a history of skin cancer.

135
00:11:09,129 --> 00:11:11,029
But you've never had it.

136
00:11:12,066 --> 00:11:13,266
No.

137
00:11:14,254 --> 00:11:15,440
Long-term exposure, right?

138
00:11:15,441 --> 00:11:18,920
This is only going to be
for the next six months.

139
00:11:18,921 --> 00:11:20,547
I don't see anything
to worry about.

140
00:11:20,548 --> 00:11:24,286
Wait, I-I'm paying you,
you-you work for me--

141
00:11:24,412 --> 00:11:26,563
You're trying
to run my life here!

142
00:11:26,564 --> 00:11:29,264
Wallace, Wallace, Wallace...

143
00:11:29,931 --> 00:11:33,931
You are paying me
to make you a new life!

144
00:11:34,051 --> 00:11:36,377
Politics! And in order
for me to do that,

145
00:11:36,378 --> 00:11:39,124
I gotta be in charge of
all the elements that go into it.

146
00:11:39,125 --> 00:11:41,025
It's the only way I work.

147
00:11:41,285 --> 00:11:43,471
That means, framing
the overall strategy...

148
00:11:43,472 --> 00:11:46,085
...as well as deciding
all the specifics.

149
00:11:46,160 --> 00:11:50,097
The look of the campaign,
the look of the billboards.

150
00:11:50,174 --> 00:11:52,174
Bumper stickers, what colors
they're going to be?

151
00:11:52,255 --> 00:11:55,455
It means the polling, the ads,
radio, TV, newspapers.

152
00:11:55,530 --> 00:11:58,995
It means coordinating every piece
of information out of this office...

153
00:11:58,996 --> 00:12:01,010
...to make sure it fits with
what a polling tells us...

154
00:12:01,011 --> 00:12:02,791
...the people are
worrying about.

155
00:12:02,792 --> 00:12:04,326
Or what they're
feeling good about!

156
00:12:04,376 --> 00:12:07,495
But, aside from the campaign themes,
I want to address...

157
00:12:07,496 --> 00:12:10,040
- ...some of my long-term plans!
- Yes, I'm sure they're great,

158
00:12:10,041 --> 00:12:11,432
but they're not important.

159
00:12:11,582 --> 00:12:14,006
See, my job is to get you in.
Once you're there,

160
00:12:14,007 --> 00:12:17,447
you do whatever your conscience
tells you to do.

161
00:12:48,940 --> 00:12:51,540
<i>...before the largest crowd
of the campaign.</i>

162
00:12:51,606 --> 00:12:54,538
<i>It now appears the bloody
terrorist attack succeeded only...</i>

163
00:12:54,539 --> 00:12:57,002
<i>...in adding momentum
and conferring legitimacy...</i>

164
00:12:57,003 --> 00:12:59,539
<i>...on the one-time
underdog Cepeda.</i>

165
00:13:00,103 --> 00:13:03,003
Well, Mr. Billings,
this is not good news.

166
00:13:03,585 --> 00:13:05,785
It certainly is not,
Your Excellency.

167
00:13:05,858 --> 00:13:07,958
Do you know
how it happened?

168
00:13:08,083 --> 00:13:11,083
Well, we know that none of
our people were involved.

169
00:13:11,419 --> 00:13:14,219
Perhaps, the guerillas.
I'll know more tonight.

170
00:13:14,290 --> 00:13:16,990
How will the bombing
affect us?

171
00:13:17,481 --> 00:13:19,381
It's hard to know.

172
00:13:19,820 --> 00:13:22,320
Cepeda could gather
tremendous support.

173
00:13:24,184 --> 00:13:25,384
The only thing I know for sure...

174
00:13:25,526 --> 00:13:29,126
...is that Pete St. John will milk
this thing for all it's worth.

175
00:13:29,895 --> 00:13:33,305
- Milk it?
- Exploit. Use.

176
00:13:33,802 --> 00:13:36,909
An incident like this
is tailor-made for St. John.

177
00:13:37,893 --> 00:13:39,954
He managed the Cepeda campaign
brilliantly.

178
00:13:39,955 --> 00:13:42,555
He'll probably manipulate him
into the presidency.

179
00:13:42,680 --> 00:13:44,400
<i>That is what I fear.</i>

180
00:13:45,393 --> 00:13:49,093
We have spent considerable
amounts of money down there.

181
00:13:49,336 --> 00:13:52,936
His Majesty will not be pleased,
Mr. Billings.

182
00:13:54,478 --> 00:13:56,078
Nor am I, Excellency.

183
00:13:56,301 --> 00:13:58,501
<i>These have been
difficult years for us.</i>

184
00:13:59,480 --> 00:14:01,480
Prices keep falling.

185
00:14:02,516 --> 00:14:05,091
Populists like Cepeda keep...

186
00:14:05,741 --> 00:14:08,816
<i>...nationalizing their oil
and entering the market.</i>

187
00:14:09,186 --> 00:14:12,583
Here, we have senators
and congressmen talking of...

188
00:14:12,633 --> 00:14:16,086
...solar generation and
electrical wind generators...

189
00:14:16,218 --> 00:14:19,393
<i>...and other such--
impractical ideas.</i>

190
00:14:21,352 --> 00:14:25,152
Your upcoming elections are
important to us, Mr. Billings.

191
00:14:25,778 --> 00:14:27,478
We're well prepared.

192
00:14:28,947 --> 00:14:32,247
I feel completely secure
about Senator Hastings.

193
00:14:32,634 --> 00:14:36,134
And the man who will be
replacing him in...

194
00:14:37,582 --> 00:14:40,682
- ...Oheeo?
- Ohio.

195
00:14:41,230 --> 00:14:43,430
Thank you, Mr. Billings.

196
00:14:43,779 --> 00:14:46,179
A superb candidate,
Your Excellency.

197
00:14:46,554 --> 00:14:49,254
Who will be in charge
of his campaign?

198
00:14:49,728 --> 00:14:52,028
Well, we have one of the
top campaign consultants.

199
00:14:52,104 --> 00:14:55,304
Why not... Pete St. John?

200
00:14:56,242 --> 00:14:59,042
He may be too close
to Senator Hastings.

201
00:14:59,842 --> 00:15:02,042
He may have
conflicting loyalties.

202
00:15:02,176 --> 00:15:05,976
From what I know of St. John,
he has no loyalties.

203
00:15:06,064 --> 00:15:09,164
His candidates seem to be on the left,
on the right, in the center--

204
00:15:09,775 --> 00:15:12,975
He seems to be loyal
only to money.

205
00:15:13,414 --> 00:15:15,114
And we have money.

206
00:15:16,254 --> 00:15:18,043
- I want to think about it.
- Is he the best?

207
00:15:18,093 --> 00:15:21,585
- Yes, certainly one of the best.
- Then, please, Billings...

208
00:15:21,586 --> 00:15:23,386
...do think about it.

209
00:15:23,509 --> 00:15:26,709
I don't want His Majesty upset
with another failure,

210
00:15:26,820 --> 00:15:28,520
mine...

211
00:15:29,102 --> 00:15:30,402
...or yours.

212
00:15:46,109 --> 00:15:48,109
...We can't afford you
anymore, Pete.

213
00:15:48,192 --> 00:15:50,958
Naah, you don't have to, Senator.
I'm like Mother Teresa.

214
00:15:50,959 --> 00:15:53,366
My work's only
for the truly needy.

215
00:15:53,500 --> 00:15:55,454
I ran into Phil Healston.
He said he saw you...

216
00:15:55,455 --> 00:15:57,201
...at the Aspen conference
last month.

217
00:15:57,202 --> 00:15:58,893
How's Phil doing?

218
00:15:58,993 --> 00:16:01,704
Great, absolutely great.
He said he was very impressed...

219
00:16:01,705 --> 00:16:04,142
...with the paper you gave him
on solar generation.

220
00:16:04,143 --> 00:16:05,343
<i>- He showed it to you?
- Mm-hm.</i>

221
00:16:05,457 --> 00:16:07,257
What do you think?

222
00:16:07,868 --> 00:16:09,368
What else?

223
00:16:09,571 --> 00:16:11,571
<i>If that new design works...</i>

224
00:16:11,628 --> 00:16:14,236
...shake-out will be
absolutely incredible.

225
00:16:14,336 --> 00:16:16,999
I mean, if this gets funded,

226
00:16:17,001 --> 00:16:18,987
actually worked...

227
00:16:18,988 --> 00:16:20,488
My God!

228
00:16:20,904 --> 00:16:23,249
We're talking, ten,
fifteen years?

229
00:16:23,399 --> 00:16:26,449
Just the Sun Belt alone, what,
30%-40% of the population?

230
00:16:26,450 --> 00:16:28,600
That's it for the utilities.
Gone.

231
00:16:28,601 --> 00:16:31,203
This is the fuel oil,
electric, gas, everything...

232
00:16:31,304 --> 00:16:33,350
...right down the tubes.

233
00:16:35,076 --> 00:16:36,891
This must've leaked out by now.

234
00:16:36,892 --> 00:16:40,072
You and your committee must be
getting squeezed like hell.

235
00:16:42,759 --> 00:16:44,159
God!

236
00:16:47,969 --> 00:16:49,706
When I talked
with Syd,

237
00:16:49,707 --> 00:16:52,469
naturally, given
the timing, she, uh,

238
00:16:52,525 --> 00:16:54,525
...she assumed--

239
00:17:01,071 --> 00:17:05,371
I'm not running again,
I've made the decision. It's done.

240
00:17:05,914 --> 00:17:08,914
I'm not feeling well.
I'm ill.

241
00:17:09,003 --> 00:17:11,003
That's what'll come out.

242
00:17:13,145 --> 00:17:14,745
Sam, I didn't know.

243
00:17:16,087 --> 00:17:17,444
It's over, Pete.

244
00:17:17,445 --> 00:17:21,090
I'm sorry about the campaign,
but-- it's over.

245
00:17:21,091 --> 00:17:23,391
Fuck the campaign.

246
00:17:23,747 --> 00:17:25,347
Just tell me how're you
going to be.

247
00:17:25,491 --> 00:17:26,991
I'll be all right.

248
00:17:31,301 --> 00:17:33,301
Is it terminal?

249
00:17:34,482 --> 00:17:36,182
No, it's, uh--

250
00:17:38,916 --> 00:17:42,216
After a while, when we have
some time, we'll talk.

251
00:17:42,309 --> 00:17:46,609
<i>I asked you down here, well,
first, to tell you.</i>

252
00:17:47,235 --> 00:17:50,006
Then, to ask you to help me
with the statement.

253
00:17:50,007 --> 00:17:52,924
I don't want to get
into specifics, but,

254
00:17:52,925 --> 00:17:55,055
it must be unequivocal.

255
00:17:56,693 --> 00:17:59,493
I've thought you'd be
the guy to write it.

256
00:18:00,744 --> 00:18:02,544
When do you want
this thing?

257
00:18:03,727 --> 00:18:06,293
I asked my press secretary to...

258
00:18:06,844 --> 00:18:10,127
...call a news conference,
10:00 in the morning.

259
00:18:12,409 --> 00:18:13,809
Tomorrow?

260
00:18:21,201 --> 00:18:24,000
Sam, you know you can
postpone this a couple of days--

261
00:18:24,001 --> 00:18:25,101
No!

262
00:18:31,322 --> 00:18:32,822
Okay.

263
00:18:34,894 --> 00:18:38,794
There's a few calls you're
gonna have to make tonight...

264
00:18:38,978 --> 00:18:42,178
...to let people know before
they hear it on the news.

265
00:18:42,248 --> 00:18:44,148
Yes, I forgot.
You're right.

266
00:18:45,423 --> 00:18:47,423
The Majority Leader,

267
00:18:50,585 --> 00:18:53,985
the... State Party Chairman...

268
00:19:06,825 --> 00:19:09,025
Sam, I'm really sorry.

269
00:19:12,736 --> 00:19:15,836
You're one of the three or four guys
who made a difference up there.

270
00:19:53,531 --> 00:19:55,531
- Yeah.
<i>- Mr. St. John?</i>

271
00:19:56,583 --> 00:19:57,683
Who are you?

272
00:19:58,006 --> 00:20:00,906
Arnold Billings. I'm calling
on behalf of Jerome Cade.

273
00:20:02,243 --> 00:20:04,543
- Never heard of him.
<i>- Yes, I know.</i>

274
00:20:04,650 --> 00:20:06,196
I'd like to arrange
an introduction.

275
00:20:06,197 --> 00:20:08,917
Mr. Cade will be running
for Senator Hastings' seat.

276
00:20:10,719 --> 00:20:13,889
- How did you find out?
<i>- We just heard.</i>

277
00:20:15,610 --> 00:20:17,210
He'll be entering
the primary?

278
00:20:17,363 --> 00:20:19,663
Yes, but I expect
he'll be unopposed.

279
00:20:20,489 --> 00:20:22,789
I seriously doubt that,
Mr. Billings.

280
00:20:23,233 --> 00:20:26,664
Nonetheless, that's the opinion here.
The filing deadline's the 1st.

281
00:20:26,665 --> 00:20:28,749
We already organized
to collect signatures.

282
00:20:28,750 --> 00:20:30,535
Mr. Cade is well-known
within Ohio and...

283
00:20:30,536 --> 00:20:33,236
...the Senate seat is something
he's giving serious thought to.

284
00:20:33,660 --> 00:20:34,960
You know my price?

285
00:20:35,076 --> 00:20:37,106
$25,000 a month plus expenses,

286
00:20:37,107 --> 00:20:39,576
15% override on all media buys.

287
00:20:42,532 --> 00:20:45,132
Tell me more
about Mr. Cade.

288
00:20:47,992 --> 00:20:50,192
Senator, how are you, sir?

289
00:20:50,543 --> 00:20:52,643
How are you? It's good
to see you again.

290
00:20:53,305 --> 00:20:54,505
Madam.

291
00:20:55,041 --> 00:20:56,295
I got one for you.

292
00:20:56,296 --> 00:20:58,691
Why did they put windshield wipers
on a Polish airline...

293
00:20:58,692 --> 00:21:00,483
- ...on the inside?
- Why?

294
00:21:03,240 --> 00:21:06,640
- Hey! How're you doing?
- Wilfred, you old reprobate!

295
00:21:10,697 --> 00:21:12,351
I hear you're gonna resign
from the paper and finally...

296
00:21:12,352 --> 00:21:15,052
- ...do some good in the world.
- Oh, God.

297
00:21:15,966 --> 00:21:17,666
- Good to see you.
<i>- Nice seeing you.</i>

298
00:21:18,006 --> 00:21:20,606
- My Goodness.
- Good morning.

299
00:21:22,179 --> 00:21:24,379
I was worried for a while
I was gonna break our string.

300
00:21:24,467 --> 00:21:27,467
Oh, no, I got your message.
You were in London last week.

301
00:21:27,553 --> 00:21:30,039
Yes, Leonard and I were summoned
by our news editor for some...

302
00:21:30,040 --> 00:21:32,721
...in-depth preplanning of our--

303
00:21:32,722 --> 00:21:34,191
let's see, of our--

304
00:21:34,292 --> 00:21:36,314
American election coverage.

305
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:41,364
- Wilfred?
- Yes?

306
00:21:42,019 --> 00:21:46,119
What have you heard about, um,
about Sam Hastings?

307
00:21:46,574 --> 00:21:50,274
Oh! Nothing yet.
He's supposed to be sick.

308
00:21:50,719 --> 00:21:52,581
Hm! No ideas, huh?

309
00:21:52,631 --> 00:21:54,251
Are you writing this down,
Ellen, honey?

310
00:21:54,252 --> 00:21:56,852
No, no, no.
I'm just curious.

311
00:21:57,536 --> 00:21:59,736
All I know is he--
- Have you decided?

312
00:21:59,797 --> 00:22:01,497
Oh, uh, yes.

313
00:22:02,075 --> 00:22:03,911
Have you got any freshly
squeezed orange juice?

314
00:22:03,912 --> 00:22:05,721
- You didn't have any the last time.
- We have.

315
00:22:05,722 --> 00:22:07,989
Right. I'll have
a large glass and...

316
00:22:07,990 --> 00:22:09,420
...and English muffin.

317
00:22:09,489 --> 00:22:12,934
I'll have that juice, too,
with a little vodka and ice.

318
00:22:12,935 --> 00:22:15,135
- Anything else, Mr. Buckley?
- A doughnut plain.

319
00:22:17,227 --> 00:22:20,014
All I know is, I ran into him
three weeks ago...

320
00:22:20,015 --> 00:22:22,791
...at the Gridiron thing,
and everything was great.

