00:46:19,322 --> 00:46:21,422
<i>Move it, move it!
Back it up.</i>

725
00:46:22,345 --> 00:46:25,345
<i>Back! Move on back!
Do you hear me?</i>

726
00:46:27,045 --> 00:46:29,545
Tommy, roll it up to
where the schmuck fell off.

727
00:46:34,666 --> 00:46:36,366
<i>Okay, take it back.</i>

728
00:46:37,236 --> 00:46:39,236
<i>Back, back, back,
back, back...</i>

729
00:46:40,371 --> 00:46:42,671
<i>Back... back...
OK, now forward.</i>

730
00:46:42,885 --> 00:46:44,685
<i>Slowly, very slow...</i>

731
00:46:45,696 --> 00:46:47,496
<i>Slow, slow...</i>

732
00:46:47,749 --> 00:46:49,049
...slow...

733
00:46:49,340 --> 00:46:50,482
...slow...

734
00:46:50,632 --> 00:46:51,940
...freeze!

735
00:46:54,328 --> 00:46:57,128
Okay, mark it.
Take it back to the top.

736
00:47:06,620 --> 00:47:09,320
Okay, forward. Real time.

737
00:47:10,652 --> 00:47:14,152
<i>New Mexico is a special land,
blessed with mountains, deserts,</i>

738
00:47:14,239 --> 00:47:16,839
<i>clean air and pure waters.</i>

739
00:47:16,942 --> 00:47:18,642
<i>But besides her natural resources,</i>

740
00:47:18,780 --> 00:47:21,280
<i>our state has been blessed
with its human resources,</i>

741
00:47:21,424 --> 00:47:25,224
<i>from the proud Apache and Navajo tribes
who first hunted and planted here,</i>

742
00:47:25,340 --> 00:47:28,040
<i>to our long history of people
who have journeyed here.</i>

743
00:47:28,098 --> 00:47:30,698
<i>Whether they came from Mexico,
or Europe or Asia...</i>

744
00:47:30,794 --> 00:47:32,394
<i>...or other parts of this country,</i>

745
00:47:32,478 --> 00:47:34,478
<i>they all shared a common dream:</i>

746
00:47:34,531 --> 00:47:36,746
<i>to live in a land where
their opportunities were limited...</i>

747
00:47:36,747 --> 00:47:38,347
<i>...only by their own vision...</i>

748
00:47:38,579 --> 00:47:40,679
<i>and to make this special place
even better...</i>

749
00:47:40,765 --> 00:47:43,165
<i>...for their own children
and other generations.</i>

750
00:47:43,440 --> 00:47:45,740
<i>We are surely blessed
by that heritage.</i>

751
00:47:46,054 --> 00:47:49,454
<i>Wallace Furman believes
that pioneer spirit is still alive!</i>

752
00:47:49,629 --> 00:47:52,029
<i>Wallace Furman,
a governor we can trust.</i>

753
00:47:53,249 --> 00:47:54,649
Let's go home.

754
00:48:09,747 --> 00:48:12,547
What's overriding is that
we pinpoint the audience.

755
00:48:12,774 --> 00:48:15,474
Tomorrow morning I want to go
with TV news coverage.

756
00:48:15,577 --> 00:48:17,377
But, every time we hit
a new medium market,

757
00:48:17,439 --> 00:48:20,743
we'll have live remotes set up
for the noon or 6:00.

758
00:48:20,744 --> 00:48:22,191
Local anchors don't know shit--

759
00:48:22,192 --> 00:48:24,013
even less than reporters.
This way we'll be able to give...

760
00:48:24,014 --> 00:48:25,714
- ...our message straight--
- Hold it, hold it.

761
00:48:25,823 --> 00:48:28,023
<i>On the state level, a new entry
into the Senate race...</i>

762
00:48:28,143 --> 00:48:30,143
<i>...for the seat of Sam Hastings.</i>

763
00:48:30,498 --> 00:48:33,998
<i>Phillip Aarons, an Oberlin College
History professor, who's known...</i>

764
00:48:34,125 --> 00:48:37,725
<i>...for his involvement in antinuclear
and state environmental causes,</i>

765
00:48:37,808 --> 00:48:39,508
<i>called a news conference
this morning...</i>

766
00:48:39,599 --> 00:48:42,299
<i>...to announce his candidacy
as an independent.</i>

767
00:48:43,743 --> 00:48:46,043
<i>I am announcing my candidacy...</i>

768
00:48:46,279 --> 00:48:49,679
<i>...as an alternative, and
perhaps an answer,</i>

769
00:48:49,824 --> 00:48:53,281
<i>...to the regressive,
short-sighted policies of...</i>

770
00:48:53,431 --> 00:48:56,324
<i>...Mr. Westbrook and Mr. Cade.</i>

771
00:49:00,773 --> 00:49:04,973
<i>I, along with many other
people of Ohio,</i>

772
00:49:05,288 --> 00:49:08,788
<i>was particularly disappointed
by Mr. Cade's decision...</i>

773
00:49:09,672 --> 00:49:13,672
<i>...not to follow the example
set by Senator Hastings...</i>

774
00:49:13,841 --> 00:49:16,541
<i>...in the national leadership
of the development of...</i>

775
00:49:16,619 --> 00:49:20,819
<i>...renewable non-polluting energy
offered by solar generation.</i>

776
00:49:25,119 --> 00:49:28,001
<i>I intend to use this campaign
as a sounding board...</i>

777
00:49:28,002 --> 00:49:30,257
<i>...to educate the people of Ohio...</i>

778
00:49:30,966 --> 00:49:35,066
<i>...and, more importantly,
the politicians of Ohio,</i>

779
00:49:36,252 --> 00:49:39,852
<i>as to certain facts having to do
with our environment.</i>

780
00:49:43,852 --> 00:49:45,452
<i>Pardon me.</i>

781
00:49:46,982 --> 00:49:48,982
<i>We can... no longer--</i>

782
00:49:51,927 --> 00:49:53,927
What the hell does that mean?

783
00:49:57,844 --> 00:49:59,344
Nothing. Not a damn thing.

784
00:49:59,564 --> 00:50:02,164
<i>He'll make a little noise,
feel real good, and he'll get his...</i>

785
00:50:02,265 --> 00:50:05,026
...4% from the veggies
and save-the-whalers.

786
00:50:05,027 --> 00:50:07,655
He's not going to hurt us.
They'll hate your guts anyway.

787
00:50:07,656 --> 00:50:10,156
But-- there is something.

788
00:50:11,700 --> 00:50:14,700
Our first poll's showing
a problem with...

789
00:50:14,763 --> 00:50:17,163
<i>...college-educated women
21 to 35.</i>

790
00:50:17,290 --> 00:50:19,690
<i>There's something about you
they don't trust.</i>

791
00:50:24,999 --> 00:50:27,999
- How are you today, Mr. Billings?
- Just fine, thank you.

792
00:50:51,469 --> 00:50:53,469
<i>Are you expecting a print-out
from Ralph?</i>

793
00:50:53,592 --> 00:50:54,992
<i>Yeah, I sure am.</i>

794
00:51:12,132 --> 00:51:14,532
It must've gotten caught
in the printer.

795
00:51:20,233 --> 00:51:21,995
<i>Have Ralph send me
another one.</i>

796
00:51:52,675 --> 00:51:54,005
Governor?

797
00:51:54,293 --> 00:51:55,693
Hello, Pete.

798
00:51:55,788 --> 00:51:57,688
I think we gotta talk about
the death penalty thing.

799
00:51:57,795 --> 00:51:59,795
Absolutely not.
That is not negotiable.

800
00:51:59,901 --> 00:52:02,401
I'm not talking about
backing down.

801
00:52:02,513 --> 00:52:04,413
But tell me this:
where does it say...

802
00:52:04,414 --> 00:52:06,076
...just because you gotta follow
your conscience...

803
00:52:06,077 --> 00:52:07,998
...we gotta stand still
and get kicked?

804
00:52:07,999 --> 00:52:09,761
Any thoughts on the subject?

805
00:52:09,762 --> 00:52:11,905
Yes, I do. One.
Frank Coleco.

806
00:52:11,996 --> 00:52:14,560
For Christ sakes.
The man is a Neanderthal!

807
00:52:14,561 --> 00:52:16,561
So what?
He's our Neanderthal, isn't he?

808
00:52:16,691 --> 00:52:20,004
He happens to be speaking for
a constituency we could use.

809
00:52:20,005 --> 00:52:23,131
- Or you wanna argue about that?
<i>- You ever actually heard him?</i>

810
00:52:23,132 --> 00:52:25,132
In the State House, on the floor,

811
00:52:25,229 --> 00:52:28,082
he said he'd pull the switch and then
drive home and eat a pizza.

812
00:52:28,083 --> 00:52:30,183
<i>This is very, very simple.</i>

813
00:52:30,472 --> 00:52:33,682
He crosses the line, endorses
the opposition, we start to bleed.

814
00:52:33,683 --> 00:52:34,817
Come on, Pete!

815
00:52:34,818 --> 00:52:36,818
You got any guarantees he won't?

816
00:52:37,180 --> 00:52:40,280
I put out a wire.
What do I hear?

817
00:52:40,937 --> 00:52:44,329
It turns out the Senator's
next greatest passion,

818
00:52:44,330 --> 00:52:47,030
next to frying convicts,
is high school football,

819
00:52:47,244 --> 00:52:49,509
specifically, Eagle Lake High,

820
00:52:49,510 --> 00:52:52,010
<i>where Frank Jr. happens to be
starting left tackle.</i>

821
00:52:52,654 --> 00:52:54,701
He's so proud of the kid
he goes out and buys him...

822
00:52:54,702 --> 00:52:57,980
...a brand-new Dodge pick-up.
Then, to make it really special,

823
00:52:57,981 --> 00:53:01,205
he calls the Governor's assistant...

824
00:53:01,206 --> 00:53:03,720
...for a little help
in getting plate number. 76,

825
00:53:03,721 --> 00:53:05,027
Frank Jr.'s football number.

826
00:53:05,028 --> 00:53:07,998
- You're way out of line, pal.
<i>- Coleco calls once.</i>

827
00:53:07,999 --> 00:53:10,129
He can't get through.
He leaves a message.

828
00:53:10,180 --> 00:53:13,765
He calls back again. The Governor's
assistant is still in conference.

829
00:53:13,766 --> 00:53:17,163
His secretary calls back
two days later...

830
00:53:17,164 --> 00:53:21,092
...and says his request for
plate 76 will be considered!

831
00:53:21,093 --> 00:53:22,593
What is the thought there?

832
00:53:22,735 --> 00:53:25,359
You're turning a philosophical
disagreement into a vendetta?

833
00:53:25,360 --> 00:53:26,825
Our office has never delivered--

834
00:53:26,826 --> 00:53:29,826
Just get him the goddamn plate,
all right?!

835
00:53:57,262 --> 00:54:00,062
<i>Well, as you know, I've lived
in this state all my life.</i>

836
00:54:00,189 --> 00:54:01,989
<i>And I've got
a lot of confidence...</i>

837
00:54:01,990 --> 00:54:04,577
...in the plain horse sense
of the voters of New Mexico.

838
00:54:04,720 --> 00:54:08,001
That they'll be able to see
the real issues of this campaign,

839
00:54:08,002 --> 00:54:11,602
who has the experience and
the proven ability to lead...

840
00:54:11,923 --> 00:54:14,623
...and that we simply
cannot afford...

841
00:54:14,771 --> 00:54:18,471
...a governor who needs
on-the-job training.

842
00:54:18,698 --> 00:54:20,998
Thank you very much, ladies and
gentlemen. Pardon me.

843
00:54:22,262 --> 00:54:24,262
Hi there!
Thanks, people. Thanks.

844
00:54:24,410 --> 00:54:26,410
Right! Hey, you're looking good
over there!

845
00:54:26,652 --> 00:54:27,861
That's good, Frank.

846
00:54:28,011 --> 00:54:29,652
- Real good, Frank.
- I'm worried, Will.

847
00:54:29,780 --> 00:54:31,780
Oh, there's nothing to worry about.

848
00:54:31,850 --> 00:54:34,539
- He's starting to move.
- Well, of course he is.

849
00:54:34,540 --> 00:54:37,312
He started so far down
he got no place to go but up.

850
00:54:37,313 --> 00:54:39,913
But still, he's coming up
in the poll.

851
00:54:40,151 --> 00:54:44,226
Look, if can't beat some geek,
maybe we don't deserve to win.

852
00:54:44,227 --> 00:54:45,357
You're going to ice him, Frank.

853
00:54:45,507 --> 00:54:47,127
Hi, there! How are you?

854
00:54:47,516 --> 00:54:49,316
- You want him to hold?
<i>Excuse me...</i>

855
00:54:49,408 --> 00:54:50,995
- One minute.
<i>What do you think of someone...</i>

856
00:54:50,996 --> 00:54:53,606
<i>...coming from New Mexico
to be governor of New York?</i>

857
00:54:53,689 --> 00:54:56,989
<i>What? Is this a joke?
You're not serious, are you?</i>

858
00:54:57,217 --> 00:54:59,414
<i>And what about you, ma'am?
What do you think of someone...</i>

859
00:54:59,415 --> 00:55:02,008
<i>...coming from New Mexico
to be governor of New York?</i>

860
00:55:02,009 --> 00:55:04,109
<i>Utterly preposterous, young man.</i>

861
00:55:04,218 --> 00:55:06,218
<i>Not worthy of discussion.</i>

862
00:55:06,570 --> 00:55:08,007
<i>From New Mexico?</i>

863
00:55:08,008 --> 00:55:10,648
<i>Is this some kind of
affirmative action thing?</i>

864
00:55:10,860 --> 00:55:13,260
<i>A cow-boy, governor of New York?</i>

865
00:55:13,445 --> 00:55:15,845
<i>What do I think of a cow-boy
governor of New York?</i>

866
00:55:16,250 --> 00:55:18,250
<i>C'mon, will you? Gee...</i>

867
00:55:18,930 --> 00:55:20,930
<i>Crazy. Stupid!</i>

868
00:55:21,839 --> 00:55:24,139
Wilfred, you are great.
<i>McKusker...</i>

869
00:55:24,212 --> 00:55:26,412
<i>...from New Mexico
for New Mexico.</i>

870
00:55:27,008 --> 00:55:29,708
You didn't have a date or anything
tonight, did you?

871
00:55:30,409 --> 00:55:32,309
Not anymore.

872
00:55:35,558 --> 00:55:37,158
Oh, wow.

873
00:55:40,207 --> 00:55:42,207
Wallace! How're you doing?

874
00:55:44,376 --> 00:55:47,176
Yeah, yeah. I just saw it.
It was terrific, huh?

875
00:55:48,678 --> 00:55:50,578
Yeah, Wallace...

876
00:55:50,746 --> 00:55:53,446
Wallace-- look--
Stop worrying, Wallace.

877
00:55:53,551 --> 00:55:56,351
We'll be making a rebuttal
commercial tonight.

878
00:56:04,411 --> 00:56:06,311
Yeah, say it again.

879
00:56:21,245 --> 00:56:23,245
Listen, can I call you
right back?

880
00:56:23,840 --> 00:56:25,940
Yeah, right. Thanks.

881
00:57:02,695 --> 00:57:04,295
Helen?

882
00:57:10,199 --> 00:57:12,599
I want you to call Jack Rosack.

883
00:57:13,205 --> 00:57:17,029
I want him to do a sweep of the
offices, studios, everything.

884
00:57:17,030 --> 00:57:19,030
- Right away?
- Right away.

885
00:57:19,178 --> 00:57:22,978
- I want him to do the apartment, too.
- The apartment-- okay, all right.

886
00:57:27,329 --> 00:57:29,329
<i>...Wallace Furman can give
our state.</i>

887
00:57:30,128 --> 00:57:32,193
<i>He didn't HAVE to come here.</i>

888
00:57:32,194 --> 00:57:34,188
<i>He WANTED to.</i>

889
00:57:34,189 --> 00:57:36,089
<i>Wallace Furman for governor.</i>

890
00:57:36,141 --> 00:57:38,741
<i>A new vision for New Mexico.</i>

891
00:57:40,128 --> 00:57:43,228
<i>- Is that a buy, Pete?</i>
- That's it.

892
00:57:43,333 --> 00:57:46,633
<i>- I can go home now?</i>
- Let's go home!

893
00:57:51,232 --> 00:57:54,832
<i>This is the upper East side
of New York.</i>

894
00:57:55,522 --> 00:57:57,922
<i>This is Monte Carlo.</i>

895
00:57:58,052 --> 00:58:00,952
<i>This is Beverly Hills,
California.</i>

896
00:58:01,305 --> 00:58:04,867
<i>Wallace Furman could have lived
in any of these places.</i>

897
00:58:04,868 --> 00:58:08,168
<i>Instead, he chose to live
in New Mexico.</i>

898
00:58:08,934 --> 00:58:12,678
<i>Not because it was
more exciting or luxurious,</i>

899
00:58:12,679 --> 00:58:15,498
<i>but because,
unlike Monte Carlo...</i>

900
00:58:15,748 --> 00:58:17,279
<i>...or Beverly Hills,</i>

901
00:58:17,344 --> 00:58:19,644
<i>it was a place that needed help,</i>

902
00:58:20,002 --> 00:58:22,497
<i>needed the energy
and the new leadership...</i>

903
00:58:22,498 --> 00:58:25,298
<i>...that Wallace Furman
can give our state.</i>

904
00:58:25,443 --> 00:58:27,504
<i>He didn't HAVE to come here.</i>

905
00:58:27,505 --> 00:58:29,469
<i>He WANTED to.</i>

906
00:58:29,470 --> 00:58:31,552
<i>Wallace Furman for governor.</i>

907
00:58:31,602 --> 00:58:34,102
<i>A new vision for New Mexico.</i>

908
00:58:43,462 --> 00:58:45,462
What about the photo session?

909
00:58:55,629 --> 00:58:57,529
Syd! Syd!

910
00:58:57,610 --> 00:58:59,610
I've got Pete on the line.

911
00:58:59,874 --> 00:59:01,974
The newspaper you wanted me
to research?

912
00:59:08,439 --> 00:59:10,741
We just got the overnights,
we stopped the erosion.

913
00:59:10,742 --> 00:59:13,342
That carpetbagger thing
is a dead issue.

914
00:59:13,499 --> 00:59:16,979
I know you don't need to hear this,
but that mansion spot was brilliant.

915
00:59:17,125 --> 00:59:19,688
Yeah, that was great.
Look, I'm going to be here one...

916
00:59:19,689 --> 00:59:21,889
...maybe two more days,
and then back to New York.

917
00:59:21,981 --> 00:59:23,391
I want to go over this stuff
that Mitch sent,

918
00:59:23,392 --> 00:59:25,992
then we have to talk about
the rehearsal for the debate.

919
00:59:27,165 --> 00:59:30,165
<i>Oh, almost forgot
the best part. Listen.</i>

920
00:59:31,333 --> 00:59:33,333
The story going around
down there is that...

921
00:59:33,538 --> 00:59:36,038
...McKusker got the new numbers...

922
00:59:36,181 --> 00:59:38,281
...and he panicked.

923
00:59:38,416 --> 00:59:42,016
I have it from two sources
that he fired Wilfred Buckley...

924
00:59:42,117 --> 00:59:44,317
<i>...and he hired John Dietrich.</i>

925
00:59:47,157 --> 00:59:49,157
Isn't that incredible?

926
01:00:00,997 --> 01:00:02,797
Jerome.

927
01:00:05,409 --> 01:00:07,109
Yeah, Billings?

928
01:00:10,030 --> 01:00:12,830
- He's doing everything he should?
- Mm-hmm.

929
01:00:13,031 --> 01:00:15,109
- The quality is...?
- Well, you've seen it.

930
01:00:15,110 --> 01:00:17,310
The polling, the ads.
First rate.

931
01:00:19,963 --> 01:00:21,663
I don't know...

932
01:00:26,464 --> 01:00:28,464
<i>Baggage will arrive
at the low level.</i>

933
01:00:28,574 --> 01:00:32,374
<i>Buses for downtown Cleveland
are available outside main hall.</i>

934
01:00:32,574 --> 01:00:34,574
Thanks for meeting me, Pete.

935
01:00:34,730 --> 01:00:37,124
I thought you'd get out
of all the traveling this year.

936
01:00:37,125 --> 01:00:38,925
So did I!

937
01:00:39,507 --> 01:00:42,907
- Spoken to Sam recently?
- Last week.

938
01:00:43,121 --> 01:00:45,121
Talked about his illness?

939
01:00:46,005 --> 01:00:47,705
Off the record.

940
01:00:48,484 --> 01:00:49,984
Not much.

941
01:00:50,287 --> 01:00:52,090
Mostly about whether or not
he's going to stay in Washington...

942
01:00:52,091 --> 01:00:54,005
...and practice law...

943
01:00:54,006 --> 01:00:56,006
...or go back to Ohio.

944
01:00:56,919 --> 01:00:58,719
I don't think he's ill.

945
01:00:59,212 --> 01:01:00,812
Is that so?

946
01:01:02,579 --> 01:01:04,069
I'm curious,

947
01:01:04,219 --> 01:01:08,479
how much do you actually know
about Sam? Financially, I mean.

948
01:01:09,312 --> 01:01:12,112
He's never had that much.
It's just his salary.

949
01:01:12,439 --> 01:01:14,239
And Claire?

950
01:01:14,607 --> 01:01:16,607
Her family's got dough.

951
