1188
01:18:12,264 --> 01:18:13,304
Jack?

1189
01:18:13,305 --> 01:18:16,000
Pete, you're going to have to
fly back to New York commercial.

1190
01:18:16,001 --> 01:18:19,511
- I've already booked you.
- All right, what's the matter?

1191
01:18:19,594 --> 01:18:22,094
I got back from dinner
and the airplane was gone.

1192
01:18:22,369 --> 01:18:25,269
The guys in the hangar said
a truck hooked it up and towed it.

1193
01:18:25,396 --> 01:18:27,296
They thought I knew about it.

1194
01:18:27,381 --> 01:18:31,206
We found it way the hell and back
by the old runway.

1195
01:18:31,207 --> 01:18:32,915
Whoever it was,
went through it,

1196
01:18:32,916 --> 01:18:35,116
but I can't find
anything gone.

1197
01:18:35,282 --> 01:18:39,061
I've got to hold it here and
have it checked out tomorrow.

1198
01:18:39,062 --> 01:18:42,062
Do you have any idea
what the hell is going on here?

1199
01:18:44,749 --> 01:18:46,349
<i>You have a visitor.</i>

1200
01:18:46,484 --> 01:18:47,984
<i>Mr. Buckley.</i>

1201
01:18:49,739 --> 01:18:51,339
Send him in, Helen.

1202
01:18:58,987 --> 01:19:00,987
Ohhh, my!

1203
01:19:01,965 --> 01:19:04,165
I thought you never
came around these parts.

1204
01:19:05,963 --> 01:19:07,763
Yeah... Oh!

1205
01:19:08,061 --> 01:19:10,049
I read someplace, uh--
Reader's Digest,

1206
01:19:10,050 --> 01:19:11,705
that life is dynamic
and you got to--

1207
01:19:11,704 --> 01:19:14,604
keep trying new things--
you got to-- I...

1208
01:19:16,184 --> 01:19:19,184
I couldn't believe it when I heard
about the McKusker thing.

1209
01:19:20,086 --> 01:19:22,686
It wouldn't be the first time
I had a butt-head firing me.

1210
01:19:24,216 --> 01:19:26,016
- What's that-- over there...?
- Yeah, go ahead.

1211
01:19:26,155 --> 01:19:27,655
Oh, thank you!

1212
01:19:27,761 --> 01:19:30,161
Ah, it was a good lesson.
We'd lost focus.

1213
01:19:30,623 --> 01:19:32,323
He's crapping in his pants
all the time about...

1214
01:19:32,458 --> 01:19:34,458
...what you're going to do next.

1215
01:19:34,776 --> 01:19:36,576
I just let it get away from me.

1216
01:19:36,639 --> 01:19:38,939
What's this--? Ooh!

1217
01:19:40,141 --> 01:19:42,141
Yeah, I lost control
of the terrain.

1218
01:19:42,231 --> 01:19:45,731
Started reacting, and sure as shit,
start losing the battle.

1219
01:19:47,344 --> 01:19:48,844
What now?

1220
01:19:49,207 --> 01:19:51,707
I'm going to be in Ohio.

1221
01:19:51,955 --> 01:19:53,955
- Ohio?
- Mm-hmm.

1222
01:19:54,145 --> 01:19:58,408
- Westbrook-- You with Westbrook?
- No, with college professor Aarons.

1223
01:20:01,658 --> 01:20:04,058
Why, Will?
The guy's a loser.

1224
01:20:04,178 --> 01:20:05,978
Well, it's real simple.

1225
01:20:06,260 --> 01:20:08,875
He's smart, he's straight,
he needs the help,

1226
01:20:08,876 --> 01:20:10,476
and I need the work.

1227
01:20:10,503 --> 01:20:12,503
I'm going down there,
pull another 6 or 8 points,

1228
01:20:12,622 --> 01:20:14,622
double his share--
it ain't impossible.

1229
01:20:14,770 --> 01:20:18,270
What he got going now, it'll make me
look like a fuckin' miracle worker.

1230
01:20:18,394 --> 01:20:21,094
See? It's real simple.

1231
01:20:22,239 --> 01:20:23,739
Yeah.

1232
01:20:24,853 --> 01:20:28,353
Well, if they're out there,
I've seen the polling...

1233
01:20:30,467 --> 01:20:35,067
But, Will, we're not talking about
undecideds planning to vote here.

1234
01:20:35,876 --> 01:20:39,666
You got 7 weeks to identify
and roust 50,000 people...

1235
01:20:39,667 --> 01:20:41,694
...about as removed
from the system as he is.

1236
01:20:41,695 --> 01:20:45,895
That's when I figured that the votes
wouldn't be coming from Cade.

1237
01:20:53,708 --> 01:20:55,708
Are you going to make me ask?

1238
01:21:00,134 --> 01:21:01,934
Ask what, Will?

1239
01:21:02,068 --> 01:21:05,368
Your demographics, goddamn it!
The polls.

1240
01:21:05,469 --> 01:21:06,982
You're right.

1241
01:21:07,131 --> 01:21:09,669
There's no time.
There's no money.

1242
01:21:09,770 --> 01:21:11,570
I need them. Listen to me,

1243
01:21:11,629 --> 01:21:14,429
I'm calling everything in.
After this, you owe nothing to me.

1244
01:21:14,727 --> 01:21:16,327
I owe--!

1245
01:21:16,871 --> 01:21:19,971
I don't owe you anything now,
all right?

1246
01:21:20,691 --> 01:21:22,491
I left you for an opportunity.

1247
01:21:22,568 --> 01:21:25,000
You didn't want to go with the guy,
I did, so I left.

1248
01:21:25,001 --> 01:21:27,940
He was slime!
He didn't deserve getting you!

1249
01:21:27,941 --> 01:21:30,276
And I didn't deserve being left
in the middle of a campaign!

1250
01:21:30,277 --> 01:21:32,477
I didn't deserve that from you!

1251
01:21:35,048 --> 01:21:38,948
Hey-- goddamn it,
are you going to make me beg?

1252
01:21:40,993 --> 01:21:43,993
What in the hell did you do?

1253
01:21:44,093 --> 01:21:48,893
We billed Cade over $200,000
for those two polls.

1254
01:21:49,514 --> 01:21:51,358
That makes him
the biggest contributor...

1255
01:21:51,359 --> 01:21:54,659
...to the Phil Aarons
for U.S. Senate campaign.

1256
01:21:55,405 --> 01:21:57,405
It's illegal.

1257
01:21:59,534 --> 01:22:01,534
And it's stupid.

1258
01:22:10,721 --> 01:22:12,821
We're running
short of time.

1259
01:22:13,088 --> 01:22:17,388
From now on, this campaign
frames a single question:

1260
01:22:17,774 --> 01:22:20,174
"Is it or isn't it
time for a change?"

1261
01:22:21,040 --> 01:22:22,643
<i>Now, we reshape the question,</i>

1262
01:22:22,644 --> 01:22:24,444
<i>and make the other two guys
part of the problem.</i>

1263
01:22:24,517 --> 01:22:26,994
But, the critical thing is,
we don't get bogged down...

1264
01:22:26,995 --> 01:22:28,895
...trying to come up
with the answers!

1265
01:22:28,962 --> 01:22:30,938
<i>By November, there's going to be
a feel out there...</i>

1266
01:22:30,939 --> 01:22:32,929
<i>...that you can do a better job
to find them.</i>

1267
01:22:32,930 --> 01:22:34,990
- Look, I know you're--
- Phillip!

1268
01:22:35,130 --> 01:22:37,821
I could squeeze you out the whole
foot and a half of bullshit,

1269
01:22:37,822 --> 01:22:40,248
but neither of us has the time.

1270
01:22:40,348 --> 01:22:43,331
Everything I learned in the last
26 years boils down to this:

1271
01:22:43,332 --> 01:22:46,920
if they like you,
they'll vote for you. Period.

1272
01:22:46,921 --> 01:22:48,960
People don't vote issues,
they vote people.

1273
01:22:48,961 --> 01:22:50,246
Yeah, but the whole point of--

1274
01:22:50,247 --> 01:22:53,147
Phillip, you're the best guy
running, am I right?

1275
01:22:53,538 --> 01:22:56,938
I wouldn't be here
if I didn't believe that, right?

1276
01:22:57,967 --> 01:23:00,167
I think that's why you called me,
in the first place.

1277
01:23:02,486 --> 01:23:05,186
Now, the leaves
are starting to turn.

1278
01:23:05,381 --> 01:23:07,850
We got a debate
coming up, Phillip,

1279
01:23:07,900 --> 01:23:10,100
with statewide exposure.

1280
01:23:10,672 --> 01:23:12,872
You got a question
you got to answer:

1281
01:23:13,357 --> 01:23:15,257
Phillip,

1282
01:23:15,337 --> 01:23:18,137
are you running for office
or running for principle?

1283
01:23:22,042 --> 01:23:23,842
I hope I'm running for both.

1284
01:23:25,555 --> 01:23:27,655
Oh, Phillip... Phillip!

1285
01:23:27,749 --> 01:23:30,276
I'm personally convinced you'll do
a hell of a job once you get in,

1286
01:23:30,275 --> 01:23:33,075
but you got to get
through that door!

1287
01:23:33,994 --> 01:23:36,294
What's the price of admission?

1288
01:23:36,796 --> 01:23:39,106
<i>Why just kiss off
the middle class?</i>

1289
01:23:40,118 --> 01:23:42,118
I've seen some intriguing numbers.

1290
01:23:42,224 --> 01:23:44,224
A lot of them out there
like what you're saying,

1291
01:23:44,368 --> 01:23:46,168
but they're not going to
vote for you. You know why?

1292
01:23:46,259 --> 01:23:49,108
Because they don't really know you.
They think they know you.

1293
01:23:49,208 --> 01:23:50,408
They see you
without a tie,

1294
01:23:50,522 --> 01:23:52,422
wearing an old beat-up jacket
and chinos...

1295
01:23:52,534 --> 01:23:54,134
They get frightened!

1296
01:23:54,268 --> 01:23:56,168
We're throwing those votes away!

1297
01:23:56,266 --> 01:23:58,643
On the gut issues, you're not
that far away from them.

1298
01:23:58,644 --> 01:24:00,991
You got to ease off on the ones
that you are, though.

1299
01:24:00,992 --> 01:24:02,492
Look, Phil.

1300
01:24:02,554 --> 01:24:04,154
They're scared about the future.

1301
01:24:04,259 --> 01:24:06,463
Whether or not they're going to
have a job next year.

1302
01:24:06,464 --> 01:24:08,364
You got to make sure
they really listen to you.

1303
01:24:08,606 --> 01:24:11,192
They all turn off when you
stand up wearing a flannel shirt,

1304
01:24:11,193 --> 01:24:14,993
and hiking boots, looking like you
just came off a picket line.

1305
01:24:17,654 --> 01:24:20,954
Yeah. That's all you got to do.

1306
01:24:29,828 --> 01:24:32,828
- Are you through with the file?
- Yes, I think so.

1307
01:24:32,881 --> 01:24:34,881
I just want to make quite sure,

1308
01:24:34,941 --> 01:24:37,341
if there were any outstanding notes
on their property,

1309
01:24:37,459 --> 01:24:40,759
any liens, things like that,
it would be recorded here?

1310
01:24:40,931 --> 01:24:43,198
Well, are they residents here
and is the property here?

1311
01:24:43,199 --> 01:24:45,368
- Yes, Georgetown.
- Then, it'll be here.

1312
01:24:45,369 --> 01:24:47,069
Okay.

1313
01:24:47,518 --> 01:24:49,318
Thank you.

1314
01:24:56,221 --> 01:24:58,021
Yeah, Ellen.

1315
01:24:58,131 --> 01:24:59,831
<i>All right, fellows,
bring the boxes in here.</i>

1316
01:24:59,979 --> 01:25:01,479
What?

1317
01:25:02,281 --> 01:25:05,033
- What is going on out there?
- The pipes in the basement burst.

1318
01:25:05,034 --> 01:25:06,917
There's 6 inches of water
down there.

1319
01:25:06,918 --> 01:25:08,518
Yeah, say it again.

1320
01:25:10,785 --> 01:25:12,985
No, don't say it
over the phone.

1321
01:25:13,911 --> 01:25:15,911
I'll meet you there.

1322
01:25:16,349 --> 01:25:19,049
4:30, right?
Yeah, bye.

1323
01:25:20,337 --> 01:25:22,337
What time will you be back?

1324
01:25:24,503 --> 01:25:26,303
<i>It never opened.</i>

1325
01:25:27,154 --> 01:25:29,728
The construction costs went
way over budget and...

1326
01:25:29,729 --> 01:25:32,429
...they couldn't get the rents
they were asking.

1327
01:25:32,826 --> 01:25:34,626
I don't get it.

1328
01:25:35,811 --> 01:25:39,811
The owner is the Liberty Mall
Development Corporation.

1329
01:25:41,629 --> 01:25:43,629
General partners...

1330
01:25:45,354 --> 01:25:48,354
...Arnold Billings and
Claire Hastings.

1331
01:25:52,339 --> 01:25:54,727
He advanced me some money.

1332
01:25:54,776 --> 01:25:56,633
A lot of money...

1333
01:25:56,634 --> 01:25:58,834
...for my share
in the partnership.

1334
01:25:59,138 --> 01:26:01,138
<i>Well, I bought this house and--</i>

1335
01:26:01,314 --> 01:26:05,114
redecoration got out of control,
I took a second advance.

1336
01:26:05,680 --> 01:26:08,680
in anticipation of profits,
when they--

1337
01:26:08,907 --> 01:26:10,811
<i>sold the share to the
limited partners...</i>

1338
01:26:10,812 --> 01:26:13,112
...and the rents
started coming in.

1339
01:26:14,018 --> 01:26:18,218
That whole neighborhood was due
for urban renewal,

1340
01:26:18,443 --> 01:26:22,243
until it got killed
in some goddamn committee.

1341
01:26:22,912 --> 01:26:25,533
And, ludicrous as it may seem,

1342
01:26:25,534 --> 01:26:27,989
I still believed, even then,
that in the end...

1343
01:26:27,990 --> 01:26:30,900
...everything was going to
turn out all right.

1344
01:26:31,425 --> 01:26:34,125
When did Billings
start leaning on you?

1345
01:26:35,596 --> 01:26:37,596
<i>In January.</i>

1346
01:26:38,633 --> 01:26:41,571
He said a couple of clients
would be hurt...

1347
01:26:41,572 --> 01:26:43,918
...by the new solar design
and he asked me...

1348
01:26:43,919 --> 01:26:47,063
...to persuade Sam
to stop pushing it.

1349
01:26:47,064 --> 01:26:50,034
I told him he was crazy!
I mean, my God, Sam--

1350
01:26:50,035 --> 01:26:51,992
wouldn't listen to me
on the abortion!

1351
01:26:51,993 --> 01:26:55,893
It was damned sure he wouldn't
listen on solar generation.

1352
01:26:56,333 --> 01:26:59,107
This went on for a month,
six weeks,

1353
01:26:59,207 --> 01:27:03,107
and then, he brought up
a surprise:

1354
01:27:04,121 --> 01:27:05,921
the money.

1355
01:27:08,315 --> 01:27:10,615
How much money
did he give you?

1356
01:27:13,563 --> 01:27:16,063
380,000 dollars.

1357
01:27:16,722 --> 01:27:18,722
<i>A little more.</i>

1358
01:27:21,036 --> 01:27:23,153
What was so funny
was I thought...

1359
01:27:23,154 --> 01:27:25,754
...that I could handle it--
and him!

1360
01:27:26,430 --> 01:27:28,000
Even when he started to...

1361
01:27:28,001 --> 01:27:29,944
...come to the house and
show up all the time,

1362
01:27:29,945 --> 01:27:31,645
I still thought that I--

1363
01:27:31,736 --> 01:27:34,236
it was only a little kind
of intimidation.

1364
01:27:34,636 --> 01:27:36,331
And then, one day, he--

1365
01:27:36,480 --> 01:27:39,536
walked right past me
into Sam's office, and...

1366
01:27:40,513 --> 01:27:43,613
...laid it on the line.
Laid it on the line!

1367
01:27:43,695 --> 01:27:46,295
And he asked Sam
to kill the appropriation.

1368
01:27:46,350 --> 01:27:50,650
Sam threw him out of the house!
And then--

1369
01:27:50,736 --> 01:27:52,111
because of me, because--

1370
01:27:52,161 --> 01:27:55,636
of what might happen to me,

1371
01:27:55,785 --> 01:27:57,716
he's walking away
from a job...

1372
01:27:57,717 --> 01:28:01,485
...that he's put his life
and soul into.

1373
01:28:04,296 --> 01:28:07,596
Remember when you
were here last...

1374
01:28:08,148 --> 01:28:11,748
...and you spoke about friendship?
You didn't tell me...

1375
01:28:11,872 --> 01:28:14,001
...that you had come here
to dig up something on us, but...

1376
01:28:14,002 --> 01:28:17,618
...after you had left,
I knew why you had come!

1377
01:28:17,718 --> 01:28:22,118
That was one thing I could
figure out for myself!

1378
01:28:28,432 --> 01:28:30,832
When you write this,

1379
01:28:31,854 --> 01:28:35,154
make sure I am the monster.

1380
01:28:42,999 --> 01:28:45,579
Right, right, right.
Just send it to me. If, uh,

1381
01:28:45,578 --> 01:28:49,293
if I have any questions
I'll get back to you.

1382
01:28:50,043 --> 01:28:51,678
Yeah, okay.

1383
01:28:58,703 --> 01:29:02,003
I had a long talk with
Claire Hastings last night.

1384
01:29:03,902 --> 01:29:06,892
Well, I happen to know
Mrs. Hastings quite well.

1385
01:29:06,992 --> 01:29:10,520
I don't know if she told you,
but we were business partners.

1386
01:29:11,148 --> 01:29:12,948
<i>I'm out.</i>

1387
01:29:14,141 --> 01:29:15,975
I assume that means
you're resigning from...

1388
01:29:15,976 --> 01:29:18,876
...the Cade campaign. Is that
what you mean, Mr. St. John?

1389
01:29:19,395 --> 01:29:22,395
The plane. The phones.

1390
01:29:23,412 --> 01:29:27,012
Two clients canceling out,
what was the point?

1391
01:29:34,945 --> 01:29:37,845
The point-- to what?
The point is...

1392
01:29:38,247 --> 01:29:40,247
...I didn't trust you, okay?

1393
01:29:40,719 --> 01:29:43,419
I didn't want you
on this campaign.

1394
01:29:43,575 --> 01:29:46,051
One, you're much too close
to Hastings and, out of nowhere,

1395
01:29:46,052 --> 01:29:47,989
this Aarons jumps in the race,

1396
01:29:47,990 --> 01:29:51,006
and your old pal Buckley
is calling the shots on that one?

1397
01:29:51,007 --> 01:29:53,007
No, no.

1398
01:29:54,327 --> 01:29:56,327
Look,

1399
01:29:56,716 --> 01:29:59,816
we hired you to do a job,
Mr. St. John,

1400
01:29:59,999 --> 01:30:03,000
<i>and it wasn't to investigate
me and my company...</i>

1401
01:30:03,001 --> 01:30:06,301
<i>...and it sure wasn't to exchange
information with your ex-wife.</i>

1402
01:30:10,679 --> 01:30:12,406
Look, we wanted you to know...

1403
01:30:12,407 --> 01:30:15,690
...that if you really
did try and screw us,

1404
01:30:15,691 --> 01:30:18,991
that something bad
could happen to you.

1405
01:30:19,215 --> 01:30:21,392
That's the message
we were trying to convey.

1406
01:30:21,393 --> 01:30:24,413
Now, the plane,
the phones...

1407
01:30:25,035 --> 01:30:27,635
...merely dramatic illustrations.

1408
01:30:31,005 --> 01:30:33,405
Don't you walk out on me.

1409
01:30:33,850 --> 01:30:36,383
Oh, you think it's all
some kinda game, don't you?

1410
01:30:36,384 --> 01:30:39,984
You just walk in,
you jerk the locals around,

1411
01:30:40,003 --> 01:30:43,003
you put in whoever's paying you
and you leave.

1412
01:30:43,129 --> 01:30:45,929
It is no fucking game!

1413
01:30:46,053 --> 01:30:48,453
You are deciding
who's running this country,

1414
01:30:48,528 --> 01:30:51,025
who's running other countries.
I care about that.

1415
01:30:51,325 --> 01:30:53,586
My clients have to deal
with the consequences.

1416
01:30:53,587 --> 01:30:55,587
You don't give a shit!

1417
01:31:04,140 --> 01:31:06,140
Look, I, uh--

1418
01:31:07,037 --> 01:31:09,230
Come on, we're the same guys,
you and me.

1419
01:31:09,231 --> 01:31:12,990
Why don't you just do
what you've always done?

1420
01:31:13,001 --> 01:31:16,383
Just elect Cade,
and get paid,

1421
01:31:16,450 --> 01:31:18,450
and leave.

1422
01:31:20,195 --> 01:31:22,695
What is the problem, Peter?

1423
01:32:26,687 --> 01:32:28,487
I hate this.

1424
01:32:29,248 --> 01:32:31,848
You're going to do good, Phillip.
Real good.

1425
01:32:31,966 --> 01:32:33,466
- I've got an idea.
- What?

1426
01:32:33,538 --> 01:32:35,838
Instead of me trying
to impersonate a statesman,

1427
01:32:35,839 --> 01:32:37,841
when it's my turn to speak
maybe we should just...

1428
01:32:37,842 --> 01:32:41,142
...turn down the lights and run
"Mr. Smith Goes to Washington".

1429
01:32:41,701 --> 01:32:42,950
Now we're starting to move.

1430
01:32:42,951 --> 01:32:44,408
You could feel it
on our last trip.

1431
01:32:44,409 --> 01:32:47,409
You're framing the right message
and it's getting through.

1432
01:32:52,980 --> 01:32:54,280
Will--

1433
01:32:54,587 --> 01:32:56,987
I know this is a real bad time.
Could I have a couple of minutes?

1434
01:32:57,062 --> 01:32:59,962
Yeah, you're right, it is bad.
We're just on our way out.

1435
01:33:00,131 --> 01:33:01,931
Phillip, this is Pete St. John.

1436
01:33:02,001 --> 01:33:03,459
I've read about you.

1437
01:33:04,015 --> 01:33:05,415
Yeah. Hello.

1438
01:33:05,493 --> 01:33:07,393
We'll talk later, uh?

1439
01:33:07,501 --> 01:33:11,640
Look, I gave you two polls.
You can give me two minutes.

1440
01:33:11,641 --> 01:33:14,641
What did I give you?
What did you do with it?

1441
01:33:15,735 --> 01:33:19,035
I sold out! All right, Will?
I sold out!

1442
01:33:19,481 --> 01:33:21,292
He thinks because he won't work
for someone like Cade,

1443
01:33:21,393 --> 01:33:23,017
...makes everything okay.
It makes me a shit...

1444
01:33:23,118 --> 01:33:26,610
...and him, some kind of
a holy crusader. We're the same!

1445
01:33:27,168 --> 01:33:29,268
He got you this suit, right?

1446
01:33:29,462 --> 01:33:32,462
New haircut. Contacts.

1447
01:33:33,937 --> 01:33:37,337
And what you've been saying
has started to shift?

1448
01:33:38,398 --> 01:33:39,958
Have you softened anything
you were saying...

1449
01:33:39,959 --> 01:33:42,136
...before he came along
to help you out?

1450
01:33:42,829 --> 01:33:44,585
Hmm? Well, that's OK.

1451
01:33:44,586 --> 01:33:47,186
That's his job, to get you in.

1452
01:33:47,358 --> 01:33:50,958
Once you're elected, you can do
anything you want to do.

1453
01:33:51,356 --> 01:33:53,156
That sound familiar?

1454
01:33:55,648 --> 01:33:57,578
Look, I know I'm going to
hurt your feelings, but...

1455
01:33:57,579 --> 01:33:59,083
...you don't have a chance.

1456
01:33:59,084 --> 01:34:01,235
- You got a lot of gall--
- No, no, no, no--

1457
01:34:01,236 --> 01:34:02,836
It's OK, Wilfred.
I want to hear this.

1458
01:34:02,971 --> 01:34:04,271
You're a bright guy,
you teach college,

1459
01:34:04,272 --> 01:34:07,015
just can't be news.
You do not have a prayer.

1460
01:34:07,918 --> 01:34:09,649
<i>It's just one of
those awkward realities...</i>

1461
01:34:09,650 --> 01:34:13,950
<i>...we don't say out loud
in front of the paying clients.</i>

1462
01:34:16,762 --> 01:34:18,577
Instead of just going back
and teach History...

1463
01:34:18,578 --> 01:34:20,778
...why don't you go out there
tonight and make some?

1464
01:34:21,050 --> 01:34:23,000
<i>You got nothing to lose!
Why don't you go out there...</i>

1465
01:34:23,001 --> 01:34:25,435
<i>...stand up and say
exactly what you think?</i>

1466
01:34:26,023 --> 01:34:28,023
What you think!

1467
01:34:28,355 --> 01:34:30,855
Maybe even what you feel!

1468
01:34:31,403 --> 01:34:33,630
<i>Not what the polls say,
or what Wilfred says, or what I--</i>

1469
01:34:33,631 --> 01:34:35,764
Are you saying
I can't handle my client?

1470
01:34:35,765 --> 01:34:38,963
Wilfred, I'm not talking about you.
You're the best of all of us.

1471
01:34:38,964 --> 01:34:40,856
But it doesn't mean a damn
who's running the show!

1472
01:34:40,857 --> 01:34:42,393
- It's a show!
- What do you want to do?

1473
01:34:42,394 --> 01:34:44,348
Go back to the old days?
Like it was before?

1474
01:34:44,349 --> 01:34:46,349
Have the machines
put their boys in?

1475
01:34:46,423 --> 01:34:49,028
Is that what you want?
Have the newspapers in charge?

1476
01:34:49,029 --> 01:34:52,029
Have the "Los Angeles Times"
create another Richard Nixon?

1477
01:34:52,792 --> 01:34:55,192
If you want to walk,
just walk. Go ahead.

1478
01:34:55,274 --> 01:34:57,874
You shit on your own life,
not on mine.

1479
01:34:57,990 --> 01:34:59,975
Come on, Phillip.

1480
01:35:14,577 --> 01:35:17,077
We're irrelevant.

1481
01:35:25,788 --> 01:35:28,188
But you're staying.

1482
01:35:29,551 --> 01:35:34,051
Those people there sure as hell
aren't going anywhere.

1483
01:35:38,087 --> 01:35:41,887
Can you look at 'em and
say exactly what you feel?

1484
01:35:47,055 --> 01:35:49,955
I'm not saying you may not make
a horse's ass of yourself.

1485
01:35:51,204 --> 01:35:54,204
But, just the spectacle of
something human out there...

1486
01:35:54,466 --> 01:35:58,087
...may make hordes of people
come tumbling out of their homes...

1487
01:35:58,088 --> 01:36:01,088
...in a huge tidal wave of emotion
and vote for you.

1488
01:36:05,469 --> 01:36:07,019
You read the papers,
you got to know...

1489
01:36:07,020 --> 01:36:11,156
...there's a higher voters' percentage
in Bolivia than in the U.S.

1490
01:36:12,762 --> 01:36:16,962
<i>I don't know, maybe they feel
connected to what's going on.</i>

1491
01:36:18,648 --> 01:36:21,845
Maybe it takes too much
in America-- too much energy,

1492
01:36:21,846 --> 01:36:26,446
too much attention
to follow it all.

1493
01:36:28,416 --> 01:36:31,216
Maybe that's why they like to get
their candidates predigested,

1494
01:36:31,326 --> 01:36:34,526
prepackaged, like TV dinners.

1495
01:36:37,992 --> 01:36:40,992
I've become a very rich man
believing that.

1496
01:36:45,842 --> 01:36:48,842
Prove me wrong.

1497
01:37:05,474 --> 01:37:07,304
Hi, Pete.

1498
01:37:23,165 --> 01:37:24,665
<i>Syd, come on.</i>

1499
01:37:24,708 --> 01:37:26,908
<i>We can watch from the booth.</i>

1500
01:37:34,252 --> 01:37:38,452
<i>As President of the Ohio
League of Women Voters,</i>

1501
01:37:39,269 --> 01:37:42,069
<i>I wish to personally
welcome you...</i>

1502
01:37:42,180 --> 01:37:45,480
<i>...to the United States
Senatorial debate tonight.</i>

1503
01:37:54,841 --> 01:37:57,010
The order of opening
and closing statements...

1504
01:37:57,110 --> 01:37:59,310
...was determined
this afternoon by lot.

1505
01:37:59,678 --> 01:38:02,778
Mr. Aarons will give
the first opening statement,

1506
01:38:02,827 --> 01:38:06,027
followed by Mr. Westbrook
and Mr. Cade.

1507
01:38:11,570 --> 01:38:14,370
- Mr. Aarons.
- Thank you, Mrs. Bernhardt.

1508
01:38:15,282 --> 01:38:18,004
For those of you who still
don't know who I am,

1509
01:38:18,005 --> 01:38:21,545
I'm the guy for whom this job
actually means a raise in pay.

1510
01:38:21,995 --> 01:38:23,470
<i>Ladies and gentlemen!</i>

1511
01:38:23,520 --> 01:38:25,895
<i>Ladies and gentlemen!
Ladies and gentlemen...</i>

1512
01:38:28,584 --> 01:38:30,353
<i>I would like to remind you...</i>

1513
01:38:30,354 --> 01:38:31,920
...to please refrain
from any kind...

1514
01:38:31,921 --> 01:38:34,654
...of public demonstration
during the debate.

1515
01:38:40,559 --> 01:38:42,559
I, uh,

1516
01:38:42,994 --> 01:38:45,194
feel very uncomfortable
right now.

1517
01:38:46,841 --> 01:38:49,161
I feel uncomfortable
standing up here,

1518
01:38:49,162 --> 01:38:51,062
under all these lights,

1519
01:38:51,130 --> 01:38:55,030
trying to fit what I believe in
into a 180 seconds.

1520
01:38:55,447 --> 01:38:57,247
But more than that,

1521
01:38:57,319 --> 01:39:01,019
I feel uncomfortable with the job
of being a candidate.

1522
01:39:01,532 --> 01:39:03,961
<i>With trying to convince you
that by electing me...</i>

1523
01:39:03,962 --> 01:39:05,832
<i>...to the U.S. Senate...</i>

1524
01:39:05,920 --> 01:39:07,995
<i>...you're going to get
a better job,</i>

1525
01:39:07,996 --> 01:39:10,196
<i>you're going to
make more money,</i>

1526
01:39:10,335 --> 01:39:13,535
<i>that your lives are somehow
going to magically improve,</i>

1527
01:39:15,609 --> 01:39:18,009
because that's not
going to happen.

1528
01:39:18,574 --> 01:39:21,274
It's not going to happen
if you elect me,

1529
01:39:21,369 --> 01:39:24,369
or Mr. Cade
or Mr. Westbrook.

1530
01:39:25,655 --> 01:39:27,211
Therefore,

1531
01:39:27,361 --> 01:39:30,355
I am not going to ask you
now for your vote.

1532
01:39:30,795 --> 01:39:32,545
I am going to ask
that you listen to me...

1533
01:39:32,546 --> 01:39:36,246
<i>...for the next few minutes, and
during the rest of the debate,</i>

1534
01:39:36,328 --> 01:39:39,028
<i>and then just think about
what I've said.</i>

1535
01:39:39,734 --> 01:39:43,739
I think that, above all else,
our real problems--

1536
01:39:43,740 --> 01:39:46,440
chronic poverty,
shrinking resources,

1537
01:39:46,530 --> 01:39:48,530
are long-term.

1538
01:39:48,732 --> 01:39:50,772
<i>But the solutions
we're being given...</i>

1539
01:39:50,773 --> 01:39:53,576
<i>...are designed to get
the politicians elected,</i>

1540
01:39:53,577 --> 01:39:55,777
<i>not to solve the problems.</i>

1541
01:39:55,950 --> 01:39:57,450
<i>Ladies and gentlemen!</i>

1542
01:39:57,654 --> 01:39:59,654
Ladies and gentlemen!

1543
01:40:02,010 --> 01:40:04,690
Once more I remind
the audience...

1544
01:40:04,740 --> 01:40:06,910
...not to cheer or applaud.

1545
01:40:07,036 --> 01:40:09,536
<i>You only take time away
from your candidate.</i>

1546
01:40:09,827 --> 01:40:12,327
<i>You only take time away
from your candidate.</i>

1547
01:40:12,923 --> 01:40:14,123
<i>Thank you.</i>

1548
01:40:14,338 --> 01:40:17,338
Right now,
right here in Ohio,

1549
01:40:17,805 --> 01:40:20,505
why can't we be the first
to forget about the election?

1550
01:40:20,626 --> 01:40:23,626
<i>And think past November.
And past next year. And--</i>

1551
01:40:23,780 --> 01:40:27,041
<i>maybe even beyond our own
lifetimes and begin to...</i>

1552
01:40:27,042 --> 01:40:29,642
<i>...really think about
the real answers.</i>

1553
01:40:29,877 --> 01:40:33,077
<i>If there is an early pattern
in this off-year election,</i>

1554
01:40:33,174 --> 01:40:34,708
<i>is that the voters...</i>

1555
01:40:34,858 --> 01:40:37,174
<i>...are sending a strong signal
to the politicians,</i>

1556
01:40:37,251 --> 01:40:39,451
<i>saying any politician
who takes them for granted...</i>

1557
01:40:39,524 --> 01:40:41,724
<i>...does so at his or her
own peril.</i>

1558
01:40:41,838 --> 01:40:44,138
<i>For instance, Senate races
in New York, Florida and Oregon,</i>

1559
01:40:44,199 --> 01:40:47,030
<i>had been predicted by the experts
as easy contests.</i>

1560
01:40:47,031 --> 01:40:48,431
<i>They're horse races.</i>

1561
01:40:48,564 --> 01:40:51,564
<i>Jim Hart, it's an hour or so
before the polls close in the West.</i>

1562
01:40:51,660 --> 01:40:54,160
<i>What do our exit polls
show us so far?</i>

1563
01:40:54,230 --> 01:40:57,230
<i>Roger, one contest in which
the experts appear to be right,</i>

1564
01:40:57,377 --> 01:41:00,077
<i>though it was exceptionally
bitter and hard-fought</i>

1565
01:41:00,224 --> 01:41:04,224
<i>and closer than expected, is the
New Mexico gubernatorial race.</i>

1566
01:41:04,307 --> 01:41:05,607
<i>Based on our numbers,</i>

1567
01:41:05,666 --> 01:41:08,021
<i>we believe that congressman
Frank McKusker...</i>

1568
01:41:08,022 --> 01:41:10,322
<i>...will wind up with about
53% of the vote,</i>

1569
01:41:10,516 --> 01:41:12,716
<i>defeating millionaire
Wallace Furman...</i>

1570
01:41:12,949 --> 01:41:16,649
<i>...who spend more than
an estimate of $5,000,000...</i>

1571
01:41:17,983 --> 01:41:19,983
<i>Wallace, I'm sorry!</i>

1572
01:41:22,276 --> 01:41:25,276
Oh, yeah, Wilfred called me
last week.

1573
01:41:26,777 --> 01:41:28,677
Yeah? How is he?

1574
01:41:29,271 --> 01:41:31,671
Well, he was pretty upset
when he called.

1575
01:41:31,851 --> 01:41:34,104
Something about
you storming in...

1576
01:41:34,105 --> 01:41:36,205
...like the mad prophet of doom.

1577
01:41:36,323 --> 01:41:38,623
That's the way he put it.

1578
01:41:39,222 --> 01:41:42,322
He was pleased
you left Cade.

1579
01:41:43,485 --> 01:41:45,885
But he seemed, hum--

1580
01:41:45,952 --> 01:41:49,152
upset about something
you'd said to Aarons.

1581
01:41:49,382 --> 01:41:51,682
<i>What did you say
to him, Pete? He--</i>

1582
01:41:51,935 --> 01:41:54,235
<i>wouldn't be specific.</i>

1583
01:41:55,411 --> 01:41:57,611
The truth, I think.

1584
01:41:58,150 --> 01:42:00,650
Finally, all he had to offer
was himself.

1585
01:42:07,264 --> 01:42:11,001
<i>Thank you. Based on our
ABC exit polls,</i>

1586
01:42:11,002 --> 01:42:13,326
<i>and early results from
key precincts...</i>

1587
01:42:13,476 --> 01:42:16,359
<i>...in the State of Washington,
we're now projecting...</i>

1588
01:42:16,360 --> 01:42:18,786
<i>...that incumbent Governor
Andrea Stannard...</i>

1589
01:42:18,787 --> 01:42:20,987
<i>...will win a second
four-year term...</i>

1590
01:42:21,178 --> 01:42:22,978
Thank God.

1591
01:42:24,619 --> 01:42:26,619
Well done.

1592
01:42:28,773 --> 01:42:30,273
- Well done.
- Thank you very much.

1593
01:42:30,390 --> 01:42:32,390
Thank you. Thank you.

1594
01:42:34,832 --> 01:42:37,232
You having problems
with your story?

1595
01:42:37,726 --> 01:42:39,626
How do you mean?

1596
01:42:39,722 --> 01:42:41,722
It's just that
I haven't seen it yet.

1597
01:42:42,053 --> 01:42:43,553
I'm surprised, that's all.

1598
01:42:43,606 --> 01:42:45,406
No. No, it's fine.

1599
01:42:45,494 --> 01:42:47,994
Just a-- a mess.

1600
01:42:49,466 --> 01:42:51,266
You having trouble
finding sources?

1601
01:42:51,400 --> 01:42:53,300
Oh, uh--

1602
01:42:53,910 --> 01:42:55,910
No, no.

1603
01:42:57,706 --> 01:42:59,506
What is it?

1604
01:43:00,468 --> 01:43:02,268
I, uh--

1605
01:43:02,483 --> 01:43:06,283
I just-- I decided
not to do a story about, uh...

1606
01:43:06,392 --> 01:43:08,392
Sam and Claire, that's all.

1607
01:43:09,973 --> 01:43:11,473
Why?

1608
01:43:14,478 --> 01:43:16,754
Well, first of all,
Sam didn't commit any crime.

1609
01:43:16,755 --> 01:43:18,355
He didn't do
anything wrong.

1610
01:43:18,444 --> 01:43:20,344
The only person who did
anything was Claire.

1611
01:43:20,566 --> 01:43:22,779
<i>Billings went into business
with a Senator's wife...</i>

1612
01:43:22,780 --> 01:43:24,380
<i>...and tried to influence
his vote.</i>

1613
01:43:24,491 --> 01:43:26,358
Of course, it's nasty and
it's against all the rules,

1614
01:43:26,359 --> 01:43:28,159
but it's just
a question of degree.

1615
01:43:28,246 --> 01:43:29,958
The man's basically
a lobbyist, right?

1616
01:43:29,959 --> 01:43:32,258
That's what he gets paid for,
trying to influence votes.

1617
01:43:32,259 --> 01:43:34,059
Do you know what
the real story is?

1618
01:43:34,184 --> 01:43:36,184
Foreign influence
in American elections.

1619
01:43:36,256 --> 01:43:39,256
Do you know what
I found out since--?

1620
01:43:42,430 --> 01:43:44,430
That's what's going in
next week, anyway.

1621
01:43:44,579 --> 01:43:45,979
I don't believe this!

1622
01:43:45,980 --> 01:43:48,006
Even I think Sam and Claire's
a terrific story.

1623
01:43:48,007 --> 01:43:50,499
I hate the idea of it--

1624
01:43:50,625 --> 01:43:53,125
You're not getting
human on me, are you?

1625
01:43:53,675 --> 01:43:55,275
Hey.

1626
01:43:58,205 --> 01:44:01,205
I don't believe this.
You're not blushing, are you?

1627
01:44:06,089 --> 01:44:08,389
- Hmm?
- Excuse me.

1628
01:44:10,227 --> 01:44:12,627
<i>Certainly, one of the big
surprises of this election night--</i>

1629
01:44:12,728 --> 01:44:14,328
<i>and we're having
a lot of them--</i>

1630
01:44:14,462 --> 01:44:17,008
<i>was the apparent second-place
finish by an independent...</i>

1631
01:44:17,009 --> 01:44:19,109
<i>...running for the Senate
in Ohio.</i>

1632
01:44:19,239 --> 01:44:20,639
<i>Phillip Aarons,
not long ago,</i>

1633
01:44:20,830 --> 01:44:23,330
<i>was an unknown
college History professor.</i>

1634
01:44:23,438 --> 01:44:26,618
<i>He has been beaten by
Michael Westbrook, a republican,</i>

1635
01:44:26,619 --> 01:44:29,019
<i>but now clearly,
and some say, miraculously,</i>

1636
01:44:29,500 --> 01:44:31,647
<i>he will finish ahead
of Jerome Cade...</i>

1637
01:44:31,648 --> 01:44:34,548
<i>...in a contest that
no-one had predicted.</i>

1638
01:44:35,628 --> 01:44:37,628
<i>As you can hear,
the excitement and...</i>

1639
01:44:37,684 --> 01:44:40,084
<i>...enthusiasm here at
Phil Aarons' headquarters...</i>

1640
01:44:40,217 --> 01:44:42,617
<i>...is running high and wild.</i>

1641
01:44:43,522 --> 01:44:45,522
<i>You get the impression
from these young people...</i>

1642
01:44:45,860 --> 01:44:49,160
<i>...that their man has just won
the Presidency of the U.S.,</i>

1643
01:44:49,279 --> 01:44:51,779
<i>when in fact,
he lost an election.</i>

1644
01:44:51,869 --> 01:44:55,269
<i>Phil's phools fooled
the political experts...</i>

1645
01:44:55,389 --> 01:44:58,389
<i>...by catapulting their man
from a virtual unknown...</i>

1646
01:44:58,445 --> 01:45:01,245
<i>...to a second place
in the highly contested freeway...</i>

1647
01:45:01,500 --> 01:45:03,500
We are number two!

1648
01:45:05,085 --> 01:45:07,985
